CC   This entry represents a NUDIX hydrolase domain (approximately 70-80
CC   residues) found predominantly in plant proteins. NUDIX (nucleoside
CC   diphosphate linked to X) hydrolases are a superfamily of enzymes
CC   that hydrolyse nucleoside diphosphate derivatives. The prototype
CC   protein AtNUDX9 from Arabidopsis thaliana functions as a GDP-D-
CC   mannose pyrophosphohydrolase, hydrolysing GDP-D-mannose to GMP and
CC   mannose 1-phosphate [1]. This enzyme is involved in regulating GDP-
CC   D-mannose levels and affects ammonium sensitivity through modulation
CC   of protein N-glycosylation in plant roots. The family is found
CC   predominantly in flowering plants (eudicots and monocots), with some
CC   representatives in bacteria. STRING analysis shows association with
CC   the canonical NUDIX domain (Pfam:PF00293).
